policy_summary:
Guidelines for the Scientific and Reasonable Use of AI Tools in Undergraduate Graduation Theses (Designs)

In accordance with the requirements of the Academic Degrees Law of the People's Republic of China, and to further strengthen education on academic ethics and integrity, foster a positive academic environment, regulate the scientific and reasonable use of AI tools by students, and prevent academic misconduct such as AI-assisted ghostwriting, plagiarism, and falsification, the following guidelines for the use of AI tools in undergraduate graduation theses (designs) are provided, drawing on the experiences of other universities:

In principle, students may use AI tools scientifically and reasonably, provided they obtain prior approval from their supervising instructor and ensure that the content generated by AI tools does not compromise the originality and other required competencies in their graduation thesis (design).

Prohibited Uses:
(1) It is prohibited to use AI tools for research proposal design, innovative methodology design, algorithm (model) framework construction, thesis (design) structure design, selection of research (design) topics, summarization of research (design) significance and innovation, formulation of research hypotheses, data analysis, result analysis and discussion, or conclusion summarization;
(2) It is prohibited to use AI tools to generate or modify original data, original or experimental result images, graphics, or illustrations in undergraduate graduation theses (designs);
(3) It is prohibited to directly use AI tools to generate the main text, acknowledgments, or other components of undergraduate graduation theses (designs);
(4) It is prohibited to use AI tools for language polishing or translation;
(5) It is prohibited for defense committee members or reviewers to use any AI tools to evaluate students' undergraduate graduation theses (designs);
(6) For undergraduate graduation theses (designs) involving confidential content, the use of any AI tools is prohibited, and uploading any data or images to AI platforms is strictly forbidden.

When using AI tools, students must clearly disclose the following information in the "Statement on the Use of AI Tools" section of their undergraduate graduation thesis (design):
(1) The name and version of the AI tool used, as well as the time and specific purpose of use;
(2) The specific sections of the thesis where the AI tool was used, such as the methodology or literature review sections;
(3) The content generated or suggestions provided by the AI tool;
(4) Relevant important materials prior to AI tool processing must be retained for review and inquiry by the supervising instructor or reviewers regarding the use of AI tools.

Students who violate these regulations by using AI tools in their undergraduate graduation theses (designs) will be subject to penalties in accordance with relevant measures.

Rationale:
Check framework is coded as 1: The university explicitly requires AIGC detection for graduation theses, as it conducts AIGC detection on all undergraduate graduation theses, specifies the detection time (April 22 to May 5, 2025), and clarifies the organizational responsibilities of colleges; 
Tool specified is coded as 0: The university does not specify any specific AIGC detection tool, only mentioning a unified detection platform without naming or indicating a particular tool (e.g., CNKI AI Check, Weipu AIGC detection); 
Linked to pass is coded as 1: AIGC detection results directly affect thesis approval, defense eligibility and degree conferral, as students with an AIGC detection rate higher than 30% are not allowed to apply for defense, those who fail the second detection will have a failing overall score and need to retake the course, and colleges can formulate stricter standards.
